\begin_layout Section
What Roleplaying Means
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The word 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

roleplaying
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 means many different things to different people – and every roleplaying
 game has its own idea.
 For some it's like playing a game, and for others, like writing a story
 together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Starlit Skies calls back to how we played pretend as little kids, and how
 imagination and fantasy were natural to us.
 It's a childish thing, of course, that we were supposed to put behind us
 as we grew.
 Most did as they were told – they refined that pretend into adult arts
 like theater, or improvisation.
 Others, stopped caring for fantasy, accepting that the banal was all that
 mattered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a game for those of us who didn't know better.
 In the IRC channels and Discord servers and fangirl forums of our past,
 we continued doing as we always did as kids – without caring what the adults
 thought.
 For us, roleplay and play pretend are the same thing.
 We became the characters we imagined – princesses, knights at first, and
 then the heroes of our favorite shows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We did it because pretending together was fun, not for the story or anything
 so virtuous.
 Pretend feels more real, after all, when others can decide to do things
 you could never have imagined yourself.
 The situations we imagined grew ever more complex – but the shape never
 changed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In time, we learned to pretend better.
 We learned that telling people how their character would feel and what
 would happen to them was bad.
 We called that 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

godmodding
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 and made rules against it.
 Sometimes, we added simple dice rolls, for when people wished to leave
 a conflict to chance – or decide what happens when two players just couldn't
 agree what happened.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes, those rules grew to be more complete – becoming something that
 looks like tabletop of the sorts of Dungeons & Dragons or Apocalypse World,
 but was certainly not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It became a forgotten branch of tabletop design of its own, one few designers
 felt was worthy to be passed on.
 In writing Starlit Skies, I hope to pass on that torch – to continue that
 branch of roleplaying where we dream together.
\end_layout

